{"id":"2005.06193","submitter":"Kevin Tolle","authors":"Kevin Tolle and Nicole Marheineke","title":"Extended Group Finite Element Method","comments":"24 pages, 10 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.NA cs.NA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Interpolation methods for nonlinear finite element discretizations are\ncommonly used to eliminate the computational costs associated with the repeated\nassembly of the nonlinear systems. While the group finite element formulation\ninterpolates nonlinear terms onto the finite element approximation space, we\npropose the use of a separate approximation space that is tailored to the\nnonlinearity. In many cases, this allows for the exact reformulation of the\ndiscrete nonlinear problem into a quadratic problem with algebraic constraints.\nFurthermore, the substitution of the nonlinear terms often shifts general\nnonlinear forms into trilinear forms, which can easily be described by\nthird-order tensors. The numerical benefits as well as the advantages in\ncomparison to the original group finite element method are studied using a wide\nvariety of academic benchmark problems.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 13 May 2020 07:58:36 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 23 Sep 2020 11:18:48 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-09-24"}
